The endemic Begonia socotrana of Socotra is not only a curious and unique perennial, it is highly edible.  Leaves and petioles are very tasty, lemony ..non-astringent and would make an exceptional salad leaf.
Haggeher mountains, Socotra.

There are not many places in Sudan where one would wear a coat...but there are a few areas where it actually is cold and foggy! Here with a stately gentleman and a very interesting edible sorrel species.  Sudan is truly a treasure trove of delights if you can get over occasional gunfire and tear gas attacks! Again wonderful, wonderful people just some challenging power rivalries!

One of the most spectacular root crops in the world. The so-called "Livingstone  Potato." Hard work to find them in Zimbabwe, an incredible delight, roots are peeled (foreground) and eaten raw. 
Look for this beauty in my upcoming book on edible roots of the world.

Sublime moments of reflection, The Great Zimbabwe is a surreal monument to a civilization long departed. How they created this hewn environment and by what inspiration begs answers. Among the largest of stone ruins in Sub-Saharan Africa. Zimbabwe
On Socotra visiting farmers and villagers! The origin of these giant beefsteak tomatoes somewhat baffles me. Finding lots of relic varieties.

In Botswana one encounters extraordinary diversity in Watermelons.
Many historic American " varieties" are clearly direct relatives of presently grown traditional Botswanan landraces.  I love this! More to be revealed in upcoming watermelon book.
One of the most unusual watermelons I've ever eaten... Fiberless sweet tasty flesh melts in your mouth like ice cream!!!!! What a spectacular watermelon from southern Africa.

Strange Funerary Beehives in Old Dongola, Sudan.  Searching for relic cultivars in these lost places is one of my greatest thrills! Sudan, despite its obvious challenges... war... Etcetera! has some of the nicest people I've ever met. I'm going to reveal some fantastic surprises from this expedition.

This massive Adansonia digitata in Zimbabwe gave shelter to an entire village market. The Africans have a good saying..."The best time to plant a tree was 20 Years ago, the next best time...is today!" Plant trees.....its simple, wonderful and renewable!

It was impossible to wrap my arms around this imposing giant!! The ONLY arboreous example known in the Cucurbitaceae... Meet Dendrosicyos socotrana! What a singularly spectacular specimen. Believe it or not, some trees bore edible and tasty fruit!  Is this Cucumber tree poised for domestication??? I think so!!?

La Ferme de Sainte Marthe, is one of my favorite crop diversity farms in France.  Situated in a supreme agricultural area the farm offers an incredible selection of seeds and planting material. As of relatively recently, the new super organic products store is also a big draw! Thank you, Dominique for all the hospitality! A Bientôt!

Country folk the world over still maintain the vast reserves of cultivated crop diversity. Regardless of what appears to be genetic erosion, it is apparent to me that enough variations exist to foment an explosion of new varietals should people take notice! Stop worrying and fretting, grow, cross-pollinate and grow out again, select and stabilize and voila add new genetic combos and thrills to the world! Easy and fun!
In Socotra, searching for tubers of wild edible Dioscorea species. Delightful raw or cooked. An extraordinary wild food plant that should lend to easy domestication.

In a rush to be modern, a vast part of humanity has lost connection with the earth that sustains us and all the other natural gifts of the good Lord! People all around the world are being programmed to detest physical work and then what??? Do they hope humans become vegetative? Hooked up to nutrient machines and screens to view? It sounds comical, but we are closer than it seems... I still take great joy in work and hope you reading this do too!!!!!!💥💯

Follow @explorewithjoseph for more such content.
Saltberries are one of North Africa's great fruiting plants. Berries range from super sweet/salty to pure sweet (think green grapes). All seems to depend on the salinity of the soil.
Renee Butang has some wonderful vegetable paintings. And he lives in what is likely the most beautiful village in France!
null

Strange contrasts... An ancient culture confronts the modern disposable dilemma! Hadibo, Socotra's capital is a garbage dump. Hopefully, a few more years will see a significant change in perceptions and attitude with regard to living in a garbage dump. I tried to do my part! One day I set out to rake and clean garbage; momentarily I was a viral topic... what???? A foreigner has come to clean our garbage up!!!

If there is a desolate ancient ruin worth making a trip to...the Nubian pyramids of Sudan must be one of them!!! No controls, no tourists, just you plodding through the sands of these ancient constructions. One of the most impressive archeological sites that I have visited...
NOTE It's imprudent now because a bit of a war is ensuring, but it could be memorable... We were teargassed by proximity days after this visit!! Sudan...Crazylandia!!!!!! But very fun!!!

It's hard work eating watermelons for breakfast, lunch, and dinner; someone should do it....so I do! What endless marvels. To have followed the selection processes that bring us to modern-day watermelons would have been an incredible ride. We can still try to take the adventure a bit further!!!🤣🤣
Yemen is a country that is an enigma to most. We find the people here very hospitable and kind.  Foreigners like us are very rare in these parts! Extraordinary plants!!!!

The spectacular vista of the Abbaye Notre-Dame de Sénanque near Gordes, France.  The stunning fields of lavender in this part of the Provence is another reason why the Lamiaceae (mint family) is so dear to my heart! Simply heaven on earth!
The supreme Roman ruins at Baalbek a must-visit place if you dare visit Lebanon!  Incredible.
Searching for Basil accessions along the Nile in Egypt has some peripheral benefits! Lots of archeological wonders along the route.  Spectacular discoveries of plants and history!
You know you are in former Genghis Khan territory when you see two-humped camels!

Melons and figs in Andalucia! Visiting the farms of biodiversity heroes maintaining dozens of rare heirlooms! 
Thanks to people all over the world with a passion for nature and God's gifts to mankind....I still am full of hope!  Merci au Bon Dieu, for all you have given us!
11:08 AM

There simply is a danger of too much happiness...the exposure to so much ambrosial delight has endless ramifications. All the double speech of modern technocrats seems absurd when the simple realities of life stand before you. We are born, we live, and we die...all the way along far too many modern-era folk are distracted by endless nonsense rarely noting the bounty of God around them that sustains the life of all of us. 

In this cacophony, life really is trivial. Stop and smell the melons and think profoundly about them...I do, and it is a font of endless inspiration.  Merci au Bon Dieu!
One of the most beautiful beaches in the world. This desolate beach on Socotra has till now no permanent structures polluting the vista.  My question is how long can that last?

Among Pachycauls , Adenium obesum ssp. socotranum  is quite "gnomic" , stands of these flourish and EVEN regenerate because goats learn very quickly how unpalatably toxic they are! 
Socotra the island of marvels.

The mountains that rise up from the Red Sea on the coast of Sudan get pretty chilly, an anomaly for Sudan as most places are usually roast except for cold winter nights in the far north. Here I present (without names....do your own botanical sleuthing....!) Some of the notable plants in this fog-prone montane environment!
One of the most beautiful beaches in the world. This desolate beach on Socotra has till now no permanent structures polluting the vista.  My question is how long can that last?

This is my dad in the scorching heat of the Southwest. He loves the heat and can take hours working in the sun. He isn't doing too bad, seeing as he says, I'm not even 90 yet... although he's getting close! God Bless him!
A spectacular fig variety in Uzbekistan that I got cuttings of!
This tapestry work of Central Asia is magnificent!

A spectacular melon! The giant 13-kilogram reptilian fruit has flesh registering in over 15 brix!!! Incredible. The best from Central Asia.
